#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:1
msgid "Assembly Guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:3
msgid ""
"These guidelines apply to assembly code in module-level `global_asm!` blocks "
"and standalone `.S` files. For the underlying philosophy, see [How "
"Guidelines Are Written](how-guidelines-are-written.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:8
msgid "Sections"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:10
msgid "Use the correct section directive (`asm-section-directives`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:12
msgid ""
"For built-in sections, use the short directive (e.g., `.text`). For custom "
"sections, use the `.section` directive with flags and type (e.g., `.section "
"\".bsp_boot\", \"awx\", @progbits`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:17
msgid ""
"A blank line should follow each section definition to visually separate it "
"from the code that follows."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:20
msgid ""
"```asm\n"
".section \".bsp_boot.stack\", \"aw\", @nobits\n"
"\n"
"boot_stack_bottom:\n"
"    .balign 4096\n"
"    .skip 0x40000  # 256 KiB\n"
"boot_stack_top:\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:29
msgid ""
"Place code-width directives after the section definition (`asm-code-width`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:31
msgid ""
"In x86-64, if an executable section contains only 64-bit code, place the `."
"code64` directive directly after the section definition. The same applies to "
"`.code32` for 32-bit code. In mixed sections, treat `.code64` and `.code32` "
"as function attributes (see below)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:47
msgid "Functions"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:49
msgid ""
"Place attributes directly before the function (`asm-function-attributes`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:51
msgid ""
"Function attributes (`.global`, `.balign`, `.type`) should be placed "
"directly before the function label and should not be indented. Prefer `."
"global` over `.globl` for clarity."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:64
msgid ""
"Add `.type` and `.size` for Rust-callable functions (`asm-type-and-size`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:66
msgid ""
"Functions that can be called from Rust code should include the `.type` and `."
"size` directives. This gives debuggers a better understanding of the "
"function."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:79
msgid ""
"This does not apply to boot entry points, exception trampolines, or "
"interrupt trampolines — they may not fit the typical definition of "
"\"function\" and their sizes may be ill-defined."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:84
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2320](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2320)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:87
msgid "Use unique label prefixes to avoid name clashes (`asm-label-prefixes`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:89
msgid ""
"A Rust crate is a single translation unit, so `global_asm!` labels in "
"different modules within the same crate share the same global namespace. Add "
"custom prefixes to labels to avoid name clashes (e.g., `bsp_` for BSP boot "
"code, `ap_` for AP boot code)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:104
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2571](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2571) and "
"[\\#2573](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2573)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:108
msgid "Prefer `.balign` over `.align` (`asm-prefer-balign`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:110
msgid ""
"The `.align` directive's behavior varies across architectures — on some it "
"specifies a byte count, on others a power of two. Use `.balign` for "
"unambiguous byte-count alignment."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/asm-guidelines.md:123
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2368](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2368)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:1
msgid "General Guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:5
msgid "Be descriptive (`descriptive-names`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:7
msgid ""
"Choose names that convey meaning at the point of use. Avoid single-letter "
"names and ambiguous abbreviations. Prefer full words over cryptic shorthand "
"so that readers do not need surrounding context to understand a variable's "
"purpose. Prefer names that are as short as possible while still being "
"unambiguous at the point of use."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:15
msgid "Be accurate (`accurate-names`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:17
msgid ""
"Avoid confusing names. If a name can be misread to imply the wrong meaning, "
"behavior, or side effects, it must be corrected immediately."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:23
msgid "// Good — clearly a count\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:24
msgid ""
"// Bad — looks like a collection\n"
"// rather than a numeric counter\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:30
msgid "Choose verbs that reflect the actual work being done."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:34
msgid "// Good — implies a MMIO read is involved\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:35
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:37
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:44
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:46
msgid "/* .. */"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:36
msgid "// Bad — looks like a plain field access\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:43
msgid "// Good — implies an O(n) collection pass\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:45
msgid "// Bad — sounds like an accessor returning a reference\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:50
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#1488](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/1488#discussion_r1825441287) and [\\#2964](https://github.com/asterinas/"
"asterinas/pull/2964#discussion_r2789739882)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:54
msgid "Encode units and important attributes in names (`encode-units`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:56
msgid ""
"When the type does not encode the unit, the name must. Kernel code deals "
"with bytes, pages, frames, nanoseconds, ticks, and sectors — ambiguous units "
"are a source of real bugs."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:62
msgid ""
"```text\n"
"// Good — unit is unambiguous\n"
"timeout_ns\n"
"offset_bytes\n"
"size_pages\n"
"delay_ms\n"
"\n"
"// Bad — unit is ambiguous\n"
"timeout\n"
"offset\n"
"size\n"
"delay\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:76
msgid ""
"Where the language's type system can enforce units (e.g., newtypes), prefer "
"that. Where it cannot, the name must carry the information."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:80
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2796](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/2796#discussion_r2646889913)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:83
msgid "Use assertion-style boolean names (`bool-names`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:85
msgid ""
"Boolean variables and functions should read as assertions of fact. Use "
"`is_`, `has_`, `can_`, `should_`, `was_`, or `needs_` prefixes. Never use "
"negated names (`is_not_empty`, `no_error`); prefer the positive form "
"(`is_empty`, `ok` or `succeeded`). A bare name like `found`, `done`, or "
"`ready` is acceptable when the context is unambiguous."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:97
msgid "// Good — reads as an assertion\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:101
msgid "// Bad — verb suggests an action, not a query\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:103
msgid "// Bad — negated name\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:108
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#1488](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/1488#discussion_r1841827039)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:111
msgid "Comments"
msgstr "註釋"

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:113
msgid "Prefer semantic line breaks (`semantic-line-breaks`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:115
msgid ""
"For prose in Markdown and doc comments, insert line breaks at semantic "
"boundaries so each line carries one coherent idea. At minimum, break at "
"sentence boundaries. For longer sentences, also consider breaking at clause "
"boundaries."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:121
msgid ""
"Semantic line breaks make diffs smaller, reviews easier, and merge conflicts "
"less noisy."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:125
msgid ""
"As an exception, RFC documents that are mostly read-only can use regular "
"paragraph wrapping."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:129
msgid "See also: [Semantic Line Breaks](https://sembr.org/)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:132
msgid "Explain why, not what (`explain-why`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:134
msgid ""
"Comments should explain the intent behind the code, not restate what the "
"code does. If a comment merely paraphrases the code, it adds noise without "
"insight."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:139
msgid ""
"If a comment is needed to explain what code does, first try to rewrite the "
"code. Do not write good comments to compensate for bad code — rewrite it to "
"be straightforward."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:144
msgid ""
"See also: _The Art of Readable Code_, Chapter 6 \"Knowing What to Comment\"; "
"PR [\\#2265](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/2265#discussion_r2266220943) and [\\#2050](https://github.com/asterinas/"
"asterinas/pull/2050#discussion_r2224106025)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:149
msgid "Document design decisions (`design-decisions`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:151
msgid ""
"When the code makes a non-obvious choice — a particular data structure, a "
"locking strategy, a deviation from Linux behavior — add a comment explaining "
"the rationale and any alternatives considered. Design-decision comments "
"(\"director's commentary\") are the most valuable kind of comment."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:160
msgid ""
"// We use a radix tree rather than a HashMap\n"
"// because lookups must be O(log n) worst-case\n"
"// for the page fault handler.\n"
"// A HashMap gives O(1) amortized\n"
"// but O(n) worst-case due to rehashing,\n"
"// which is unacceptable on the page fault path.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:168
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2265](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/2265#discussion_r2266220943) and [\\#2050](https://github.com/asterinas/"
"asterinas/pull/2050#discussion_r2224106025)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:172
msgid "Cite specifications and algorithm sources (`cite-sources`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:174
msgid ""
"When implementing behavior defined by an external specification or a non-"
"trivial algorithm, cite the source: the relevant POSIX section, Linux man "
"page, hardware reference manual, or academic paper."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:181
msgid ""
"/// Maximum number of bytes guaranteed to be written to a pipe atomically.\n"
"///\n"
"/// For more details, see the description of `PIPE_BUF` in\n"
"/// <https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/pipe.7.html>.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:188
msgid "Layout"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:190
msgid "One concept per file (`one-concept-per-file`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:192
msgid ""
"When a file grows long or contains multiple distinct concepts, split it. "
"Each major data structure, each subsystem entry point, each significant "
"abstraction deserves its own file."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:198
msgid "Organize code for top-down reading (`top-down-reading`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:200
msgid ""
"A source file should read from top to bottom. Start with high-level entry "
"points and core flow. Move implementation details downward so readers can "
"understand the big picture first before diving into low-level helpers."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:206
msgid ""
"Within each visibility group (e.g., a module), order methods so that callers "
"appear before callees where possible, enabling the file to be read top to "
"bottom. Place public methods before private helpers."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:211
msgid "Group statements into logical paragraphs (`logical-paragraphs`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:213
msgid ""
"Within functions, group related statements into logical paragraphs separated "
"by blank lines. Each paragraph should represent one sub-step of the "
"function's overall purpose."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:219
msgid ""
"For long functions, add a one-line summary comment at the start of each "
"paragraph when the paragraph intent is not obvious."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:224
msgid "Formatting"
msgstr "格式化"

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:226
msgid "Format error messages consistently (`error-message-format`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:228
msgid ""
"Start with a lowercase letter (unless the first word is a proper noun or "
"identifier). Be specific: prefer \"`len` is too large\" over \"the argument "
"is invalid\"."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:233
msgid ""
"For system call errors, follow the style and descriptions in Linux man pages."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:236
msgid "API Design"
msgstr "API 設計"

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:238
msgid "Stick to familiar conventions (`familiar-conventions`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:240
msgid ""
"Prefer names and API shapes that users already know from Rust and Linux. Do "
"not invent new terms for well-known operations."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:246
msgid "// Good — follows common Rust naming conventions\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:249
msgid "// Bad — unfamiliar synonyms for common operations\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:255
msgid ""
"See also: [Least Surprise](../how-guidelines-are-written.md#least-surprise)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:258
msgid "Hide implementation details (`hide-impl-details`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:260
msgid ""
"Do not expose internal implementation details through public APIs (including "
"their documentation). A module's public surface should contain only what its "
"consumers need."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:265
msgid ""
"See also: [Modules and Crates](../rust-guidelines/language-items/modules-and-"
"crates.md#narrow-visibility) for Rust-specific visibility rules; PR [\\#2951]"
"(https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2951#discussion_r2786925410)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:270
msgid "Validate at boundaries, trust internally (`validate-at-boundaries`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:272
msgid ""
"Designate certain interfaces as validation boundaries. In Asterinas, syscall "
"entry points are the primary boundary: all user-supplied data (pointers, "
"file descriptors, sizes, flags, strings) must be validated at the syscall "
"boundary. Once validated, internal kernel functions may trust these values "
"without re-validation."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/general-guidelines/index.md:281
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2806](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2806)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:1
msgid "Git Guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:3
msgid ""
"These guidelines cover commit hygiene and pull request conventions. For the "
"underlying philosophy, see [How Guidelines Are Written](how-guidelines-are-"
"written.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:7
msgid "Write imperative, descriptive subject lines (`imperative-subject`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:9
msgid ""
"Write commit messages in imperative mood with the subject line at or below "
"72 characters. Wrap identifiers in backticks."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:13
msgid "Common prefixes used in the Asterinas commit log:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:15
msgid "`Fix` — correct a bug"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:16
msgid "`Add` — introduce new functionality"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:17
msgid "`Remove` — delete code or features"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:18
msgid "`Refactor` — restructure without changing behavior"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:19
msgid "`Rename` — change names of files, modules, or symbols"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:20
msgid "`Implement` — add a new subsystem or feature"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:21
msgid "`Enable` — turn on a previously disabled capability"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:22
msgid "`Clean up` — minor tidying without functional change"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:23
msgid "`Bump` — update a dependency version"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:25
msgid "Examples:"
msgstr "範例："

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:35
msgid ""
"If the commit requires further explanation, add a blank line after the "
"subject followed by a body paragraph describing the _why_ behind the change."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:40
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2877](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2877) and "
"[\\#2700](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2700)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:44
msgid "One logical change per commit (`atomic-commits`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:46
msgid ""
"Each commit should represent one logical change. Do not mix unrelated "
"changes in a single commit. When fixing an issue discovered during review on "
"a local or private branch, use `git rebase -i` to amend the commit that "
"introduced the issue rather than appending a fixup commit at the end."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:54
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2791](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2791) and "
"[\\#2260](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2260)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:58
msgid "Separate refactoring from features (`refactor-then-feature`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:60
msgid ""
"If a feature requires preparatory refactoring, put the refactoring in its "
"own commit(s) before the feature commit. This makes each commit easier to "
"review and bisect."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:65
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2877](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2877)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:68
msgid "Keep pull requests focused (`focused-prs`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:70
msgid ""
"Keep pull requests focused on a single topic. A PR that mixes a bug fix, a "
"refactoring, and a new feature is difficult to review."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/git-guidelines.md:74
msgid ""
"Ensure that CI passes before requesting review. If CI fails on an unrelated "
"flake, note it in the PR description."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:1
msgid "How Guidelines Are Written"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:3
msgid ""
"The guidelines in this collection reflect a set of widely-recognized "
"**philosophy** and **principles** for writing high-quality software. Three "
"books have influenced the guidelines the most:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:7
msgid ""
"[_The Art of Readable Code_](https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/the-art-"
"of/9781449318482/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:8
msgid ""
"[_Clean Code_](https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/clean-code-"
"a/9780136083238/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:9
msgid "[_Code Complete_](https://stevemcconnell.com/books/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:11
msgid ""
"The guidelines are derived from **code review experience**, where we point "
"out code smells, observe anti-patterns, and fix recurring bugs. By the time "
"the initial version of these guidelines was formulated, Asterinas had seen "
"thousands of code reviews. We collected the historical review comments as a "
"[dataset](https://github.com/asterinas/pr-review-analysis) and used it as "
"both inspiration and evidence."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:19
msgid ""
"The remainder of this page moves from values to practice. The [Philosophy]"
"(#philosophy) section captures foundational beliefs about what makes code "
"understandable and maintainable. The [Principles](#principles) section turns "
"those beliefs into design-level rules that guide everyday decisions. "
"Finally, the [Quality Criteria](#quality-criteria) section defines how "
"individual guidelines are written and accepted into this collection."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:28
msgid "Philosophy"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:30
msgid "Minimize time to understand"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:32
msgid ""
"Code should be written to minimize the time it would take someone else to "
"fully understand it. This is the fundamental theorem of readability and the "
"single most important measure of code quality in this project. \"Someone "
"else\" includes your future self."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:39
msgid ""
"Code is read far more often than it is written. If a technique makes code "
"shorter but harder to follow at a glance, choose clarity over brevity."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:44
msgid "Managing complexity is the primary technical imperative"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:46
msgid ""
"No one can hold an entire modern program in their head. The purpose of every "
"technique in software construction — decomposition, naming, encapsulation, "
"abstraction — is to break complex problems into simple pieces so that you "
"can safely focus on one thing at a time."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:52
msgid "Craftsmanship and care"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:54
msgid ""
"Clean code looks like it was written by someone who cares. Professionalism "
"means never knowingly leaving a mess. The only way to go fast is to keep the "
"code clean at all times."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:58
msgid "Continuous improvement"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:60
msgid ""
"Leave code cleaner than you found it. Small, steady improvements — renaming "
"a variable, extracting a function, eliminating duplication — prevent code "
"from rotting over time."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:66
msgid "Principles"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:68
msgid "Single Responsibility"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:70
msgid ""
"Each module, type, or function should have one, and only one, reason to "
"change. If you cannot describe what a unit does without the words \"and,\" "
"\"or,\" or \"but,\" it has too many responsibilities."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:76
msgid "Don't Repeat Yourself (DRY)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:78
msgid ""
"Every piece of knowledge should have a single, unambiguous representation. "
"Duplication harms readability and maintainability. When the same pattern "
"appears three or more times, eliminate the duplication (e.g., adding a "
"helper function)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:84
msgid "Information Hiding"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:86
msgid ""
"Hide design decisions behind well-defined interfaces. A module's public "
"surface should contain only what its consumers need. Internal data "
"structures, helper types, and bookkeeping fields should remain private."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:92
msgid "Open for Extension, Closed for Modification"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:94
msgid ""
"Stable modules and APIs should be open to extension but closed to breaking "
"modification. Prefer adding new behavior through existing interfaces "
"(traits, enums, and pluggable components) instead of repeatedly editing "
"established call paths. Do not introduce extension points preemptively; add "
"them when there is a concrete extension need."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:104
msgid "Least Surprise"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:106
msgid ""
"Functions, types, and APIs should behave as their names and signatures "
"suggest. When an obvious behavior is not implemented, readers lose trust in "
"the codebase and must fall back on reading implementation details."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:112
msgid "Loose Coupling, Strong Cohesion"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:114
msgid ""
"Connections between modules should be small, visible, and flexible. Within a "
"module, every part should contribute to a single, well-defined purpose."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:119
msgid "Consistency"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:121
msgid ""
"Do similar things the same way throughout the codebase. Consistency reduces "
"surprise and cognitive load even when neither approach is objectively "
"superior. When a convention already exists, follow it; do not introduce a "
"competing convention without compelling justification."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:128
msgid "Test as the Source of Confidence"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:130
msgid ""
"Tests exist to make change safe. A comprehensive test suite should give "
"developers confidence that a passing run means the system works and a "
"failing run pinpoints what broke. Every test must earn its place by "
"increasing that confidence. A test that does not — flaky tests, tautological "
"assertions, tests coupled to implementation details — is worse than no test "
"at all."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:141
msgid "Rust-Native Approach"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:143
msgid ""
"Asterinas is inspired by Linux but is not a C port. The language shapes how "
"we think about problems: where C code relies on conventions and manual "
"discipline (return-code checking, paired init/cleanup, header-file "
"contracts), Rust offers compiler-enforced, zero-cost abstractions (the `?` "
"operator, RAII, trait bounds)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:150
msgid ""
"Learn from Linux's design, not its idioms. The result should read like "
"idiomatic Rust, not like C written in Rust syntax."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:154
msgid "Quality Criteria"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:156
msgid ""
"Every guideline carries a **descriptive short name** in kebab-case (e.g., "
"`explain-variables`, `lock-ordering`). Short names are kept **intact** even "
"as the guidelines evolve and should be used when referencing guidelines in "
"code reviews."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:161
msgid ""
"A guideline is accepted into this collection when it satisfies all four "
"quality criteria:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:164
msgid ""
"**Concrete** — Framed as an actionable item with an illustrating example "
"when possible."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:166
msgid "**Concise** — Kept short; we do not want to intimidate readers."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:168
msgid ""
"**Grounded** — Opinionated or non-obvious guidelines should include a \"See "
"also\" line with supportive materials (literature, PR reviews, codebase "
"examples)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:171
msgid ""
"**Relevant** — Included only if it has codebase examples, prevents a past "
"bug, or matches anti-patterns observed in code reviews."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:176
msgid ""
"When present, the **\"See also\" line** lists sources in the order: "
"literature; PR reviews; codebase examples. Not every guideline needs all "
"three; for strongly opinionated or non-obvious guidelines, include the line "
"by default."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:182
msgid ""
"Do not add a guideline whose only value is mechanical enforcement already "
"provided by automated tools such as [rustfmt](https://github.com/rust-lang/"
"rustfmt) and [clippy](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy). If a tool-"
"enforced convention appears frequently in review or needs project-specific "
"rationale, keep a short explanatory guideline and point to the tool "
"configuration."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:191
msgid "Below is a sample guideline demonstrating these conventions:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:217
msgid "This example demonstrates:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:218
msgid ""
"A stable short name (`explain-variables`) shown parenthetically and used as "
"the heading anchor"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:219
msgid "A one-sentence actionable recommendation followed by a code example"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:220
msgid ""
"A \"See also\" line ordered as: literature, PR reviews, codebase examples"
msgstr ""

