msgstr ""

#: src/SUMMARY.md:73
msgid "Functions and Methods"
msgstr "函式與方法"

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:3
msgid "Minimize nesting (`minimize-nesting`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:5
msgid ""
"Minimize nesting depth. Code nested more than three levels deep should be "
"reviewed for refactoring opportunities. Each nesting level multiplies the "
"reader's cognitive load."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:10
msgid "Techniques for flattening nesting:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:11
msgid "Early returns and guard clauses for error paths."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:12
msgid "`let...else` to collapse `if let` chains."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:13
msgid "The `?` operator for error propagation."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:14
msgid "`continue` to skip loop iterations."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:15
msgid "Extracting the nested body into a helper function."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:17
msgid ""
"The normal/expected code path should be the first visible path; error and "
"edge cases should be handled and dismissed early."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:25
msgid "\"Framebuffer not found\""
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:28
msgid "// ... main logic at the top level\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:32
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2877](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/2877#discussion_r2685861741)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:35
msgid "Keep functions small and focused (`small-functions`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:37
msgid ""
"Each function should do one thing, do it well, and do it only. If you can "
"extract another function from it with a name that is not merely a "
"restatement of its implementation, the original function is doing more than "
"one thing."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:44
msgid ""
"Do not mix levels of abstraction. For example, a syscall handler should read "
"like a specification; byte-level manipulation belongs in a helper."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:49
msgid "// Good — each function operates at one level of abstraction\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:55
msgid "// Bad — mixes high-level logic with low-level details\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:63
msgid "// ... 30 more lines of byte parsing ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:67
msgid ""
"See also: _Clean Code_, Chapter 3 \"Functions\"; PR [\\#639](https://github."
"com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/639#discussion_r1524629393)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:71
msgid "Avoid boolean arguments (`no-bool-args`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:73
msgid ""
"A boolean parameter that selects between two behaviors signals the function "
"does two things. Split it into two functions or use a typed enum."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:79
msgid "// Good — two separate functions\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:82
msgid "// Good — typed enum\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:86
msgid "// Bad — boolean argument\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/functions-and-methods.md:91
msgid "See also: _Clean Code_, Chapter 3 \"Flag Arguments\"."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:1
msgid "Macros and Attributes"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:3
msgid "Suppress lints at the narrowest scope (`narrow-lint-suppression`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:5
msgid ""
"When suppressing lints, the suppression should affect as little scope as "
"possible. This makes readers aware of the exact places where the lint is "
"generated and makes it easier for subsequent committers to maintain the "
"suppression."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:13
msgid "// Good — each method is individually marked\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:23
msgid "// Bad — the entire trait is suppressed\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:29
msgid ""
"There is one exception: if it is clear enough that every member will trigger "
"the lint, it is reasonable to expect the lint at the type level."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:42
msgid ""
"See also: [Clippy `allow_attributes`](https://rust-lang.github.io/rust-"
"clippy/master/#allow_attributes), [Clippy `allow_attributes_without_reason`]"
"(https://rust-lang.github.io/rust-clippy/master/"
"#allow_attributes_without_reason), and rustc "
"[`unfulfilled_lint_expectations`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/rustc/lints/"
"listing/warn-by-default.html#unfulfilled-lint-expectations)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:47
msgid "Use `#[expect(dead_code)]` with restraint (`expect-dead-code`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:49
msgid ""
"In general, dead code should be avoided because _(i)_ it introduces "
"unnecessary maintenance overhead, and _(ii)_ its correctness can only be "
"guaranteed by manual and error-prone review."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:54
msgid "Dead code is acceptable only when all of these hold:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:56
msgid ""
"A _concrete case_ will be implemented in the future that turns the dead code "
"into used code."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:58
msgid "The semantics are _clear_ enough, even without the use case."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:60
msgid ""
"The dead code is _simple_ enough that both the committer and the reviewer "
"can be confident it is correct without testing."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:63
msgid "It serves as a counterpart to existing non-dead code."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:65
msgid ""
"For example, it is fine to add ABI constants that are unused because the "
"corresponding feature is partially implemented."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:69
msgid ""
"See also: [Rust Reference: Diagnostic attributes](https://doc.rust-lang.org/"
"reference/attributes/diagnostics.html) and rustc "
"[`unfulfilled_lint_expectations`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/rustc/lints/"
"listing/warn-by-default.html#unfulfilled-lint-expectations)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:73
msgid "Prefer functions over macros (`macros-as-last-resort`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:75
msgid ""
"Prefer functions and generics over macros. Macros are powerful but harder to "
"understand, debug, test, and format. Reach for a macro only when the type "
"system or generics cannot express what you need (e.g., variadic arguments, "
"compile-time code generation, or DSL syntax)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:85
msgid "// Good — a generic function covers all types\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:90
msgid "// Bad — a macro where a function would suffice\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/macros-and-attributes.md:99
msgid ""
"See also: _The Rust Programming Language_, Chapter 20.5 \"Macros\"; [Rust by "
"Example: Macros](https://doc.rust-lang.org/rust-by-example/macros.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/SUMMARY.md:77
msgid "Modules and Crates"
msgstr "模組與軟體箱"

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/modules-and-crates.md:3
msgid "Default to the narrowest visibility (`narrow-visibility`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/modules-and-crates.md:5
msgid ""
"Start private, then widen to `pub(super)`, `pub(crate)`, or `pub` only when "
"an actual external consumer requires it."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/modules-and-crates.md:10
msgid "// Good — restricted to the parent module\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/modules-and-crates.md:15
msgid "// ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/modules-and-crates.md:17
msgid "// Bad — unnecessarily wide\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/modules-and-crates.md:22
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2951](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2951) and "
"[\\#2605](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/2605#discussion_r2720506912)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/modules-and-crates.md:26
msgid "Use workspace dependencies (`workspace-deps`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/modules-and-crates.md:28
msgid ""
"Always declare shared dependencies in the workspace `[workspace."
"dependencies]` table and reference them with `.workspace = true` in member "
"crates."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/modules-and-crates.md:33
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"# In the workspace root Cargo.toml\n"
"[workspace.dependencies]\n"
"ostd = { version = \"0.17.0\", path = \"ostd\" }\n"
"bitflags = \"2.6\"\n"
"\n"
"# In a member crate's Cargo.toml\n"
"[dependencies]\n"
"ostd.workspace = true\n"
"bitflags.workspace = true\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:1
msgid "Types and Traits"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:3
msgid "Use types to enforce invariants (`rust-type-invariants`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:5
msgid "Leverage the type system to make illegal states _unrepresentable_."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:8
msgid "Define newtypes to encode domain constraints."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:11
msgid "// Good — a `Nice` value is guaranteed to be valid\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:14
msgid "// Bad — `i8` admits invalid values for nice levels\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:19
msgid "Prefer enums over bare integers and boolean flags."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:22
msgid "// Good — access mode is constrained by the enum\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:29
msgid "// Bad — `u8` admits invalid values\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:34
msgid "Encode invariants in generic parameters where needed."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:38
msgid "// Good — only unsafe code can write to sensitive MMIO\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:43
msgid "// Good — safe code can write to insensitive MMIO\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:51
msgid ""
"Asterinas uses this pattern widely, for example with newtypes such as "
"`CpuId` and `AlignedUsize<const N: u16>`."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:55
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2265](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/2265#discussion_r2266214191) and [\\#2514](https://github.com/asterinas/"
"asterinas/pull/2514)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:59
msgid "Prefer enum over trait objects for closed sets (`enum-over-dyn`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:61
msgid ""
"When the set of variants is known and closed, an enum is often preferable to "
"`Box<dyn Trait>` for both performance and pattern-matching expressiveness."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:66
msgid "// Good — closed set modeled as an enum\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:74
msgid "Encapsulate fields behind getters (`getter-encapsulation`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:76
msgid ""
"Do not make fields public when a simple getter method would do. A getter "
"preserves naming flexibility and leaves room for future invariants."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:82
msgid "// Good — field is private, accessed via getter\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/types-and-traits.md:92
msgid "// Bad — public field exposes representation\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:1
msgid "Unsafety"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:3
msgid "Justify every use of `unsafe` (`justify-unsafe-use`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:5
msgid ""
"Every `unsafe` block must have a preceding `// SAFETY:` comment that "
"justifies why the operation is sound. For multi-condition invariants, use a "
"numbered list:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:11
msgid ""
"// SAFETY:\n"
"// 1. We have exclusive access to both the current context\n"
"//    and the next context (see above).\n"
"// 2. The next context is valid (because it is either\n"
"//    correctly initialized or written by a previous\n"
"//    `context_switch`).\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:22
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2958](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/2958) and "
"[\\#836](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/pull/836)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:26
msgid "Document safety conditions (`document-safety-conds`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:28
msgid ""
"All `unsafe` functions and traits must include a `# Safety` section in their "
"doc comments describing the conditions, properties, or invariants that "
"callers must uphold. State exactly what the caller must guarantee — not "
"implementation details or side effects."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:35
msgid ""
"/// A marker trait for guard types that enforce the atomic mode.\n"
"///\n"
"/// # Safety\n"
"///\n"
"/// The implementer must ensure that the atomic mode is maintained while\n"
"/// the guard type is alive.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:44
msgid "Deny unsafe code in `kernel/` (`deny-unsafe-kernel`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:46
msgid "All crates under `kernel/` must deny unsafe:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:52
msgid ""
"Only OSTD (`ostd/`) crates may contain `unsafe` code. If a kernel crate "
"requires an unsafe operation, the functionality should be provided as a safe "
"API in OSTD."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:56
msgid "Reason about safety at the module boundary (`module-boundary-safety`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:58
msgid ""
"The safety of an `unsafe` block depends on ALL code that can access the same "
"private state. Encapsulate unsafe abstractions in the smallest possible "
"module to minimize the \"audit surface.\" Any code in the same module that "
"can modify relied-upon fields is part of the safety argument."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:68
msgid "// Good — small, focused module limits the audit surface\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:70
msgid "/// Invariant: `next` is always a valid frame index.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/unsafety.md:78
msgid ""
"// SAFETY: `next` is always valid (see invariant above).\n"
"            // Only code in this module can modify `next`.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/SUMMARY.md:72
msgid "Variables, Expressions, and Statements"
msgstr "變數、表達式與陳述句"

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:3
msgid "Introduce explaining variables (`explain-variables`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:5
msgid ""
"Break down complex expressions by assigning intermediate results to well-"
"named variables. An explaining variable turns an opaque expression into self-"
"documenting code:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:11
msgid "// Good — intent is clear\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:15
msgid "// Bad — reader must parse the whole expression\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:20
msgid ""
"See also: _The Art of Readable Code_, Chapter 8 \"Breaking Down Giant "
"Expressions\"; PR [\\#2083](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/2083#discussion_r2512772091) and [\\#643](https://github.com/asterinas/"
"asterinas/pull/643#discussion_r1497243812)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:25
msgid "Use block expressions to scope temporary state (`block-expressions`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:27
msgid ""
"Use block expressions when temporary variables are only needed to produce "
"one final value. This keeps temporary state local and avoids leaking one-off "
"names into outer scope."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:34
msgid "// Good — intermediate values are scoped to the block\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:40
msgid "// Bad — temporary variables leak into outer scope\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:47
msgid "Use checked or saturating arithmetic (`checked-arithmetic`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:49
msgid ""
"Use checked or saturating arithmetic for operations that could overflow. "
"Prefer explicit overflow handling over silent wrapping:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:55
msgid "// Good — overflow is handled explicitly\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:58
msgid "// Good — clamps instead of wrapping\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:61
msgid "// Bad — may silently wrap in release builds\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/language-items/variables-expressions-and-statements.md:66
msgid ""
"If wraparound behavior is intentional, use explicit `wrapping_*` or "
"`overflowing_*` operations and document why wrapping is correct."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/naming.md:1
msgid "Naming"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/naming.md:3
msgid ""
"Asterinas enforces strict, Rust-idiomatic naming across the entire codebase. "
"Names must be accurate, unabbreviated, and follow [Rust API Guidelines on "
"naming](https://rust-lang.github.io/api-guidelines/naming.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/naming.md:9
msgid ""
"Follow Rust CamelCase and acronym capitalization (`camel-case-acronyms`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/naming.md:11
msgid ""
"Type names follow Rust's CamelCase convention. Acronyms are title-cased per "
"the Rust API Guidelines:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/naming.md:15
msgid "// Good\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/naming.md:20
msgid "// Bad\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/naming.md:28
msgid "End closure variables with `_fn` (`closure-fn-suffix`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/naming.md:30
msgid ""
"Variables holding closures or function pointers must signal they are "
"callable by ending with `_fn`. Treating a closure variable as if it were a "
"data object misleads readers."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/naming.md:36
msgid "// Good — clearly a callable\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/rust-guidelines/naming.md:49
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#395](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/395#discussion_r1402964415) and [\\#783](https://github.com/asterinas/"
"asterinas/pull/783#discussion_r1593335375)."
msgstr ""

